From John Nash Subject Re Is MSG sensitivity superstition In article Doug Bank writes From Doug Bank Subject Re Is MSG sensitivity superstition Date Thu Apr GMT In article David Thomas writes lots of editing out of previuos posts Here is another anecdotal I am a picky eater and never wanted to try chinese food however I finally tried some in order to please a girl I was seeing at the I had never heard of Chinese restaurant A group of us went to the restaurant and all shared different It didn't taste great but I decided it wasn't so We went home and went to bed I woke up at AM and puked my guts I threw up for so long that I'm not kidding I pulled a muscle in my Dry heaves and No one else got sick and I'm not allergic to anything that I know Suffice to say that I wont go into a chinese restaurant unless I am physically The smell of the food makes me ill and that is a psycholgical reaction When I have been dragged in to suffer through beef and broccoli without any sauces I insist on no I haven't gotten sick Funny about my wife my girlfriend at the time used to get sick after eating certain foods at various Asian restaurants and never knew She'd go pale and sweaty and then vomit A couple of us ventured a connection with MSG and her response was MSG What's that It also happened when she pigged out on some brands of savoury crackers and which I noticed later had MSG on the Don't know about double blinds but avoiding MSG has stopped her being sick at cheers John John Nash Email Institute for Biological Sciences National Research Council of Canada Cell Physiology Ottawa Ontario Disclaimer All opinions are mine not NRC's